5. Credential Security (IMPORTANT)
5.1 Why
Node‑RED encrypts credentials (MQTT passwords, DB tokens, etc.).
If the encryption key changes, credentials are lost permanently.
5.2 Configuration
Edit:
nano ~/.node-red/settings.js

Enable a fixed secret:
credentialSecret: "jetson-nodered-prod-secret",
I set “smartplug”
Rules:
Set once
Never change after deployment
Do NOT commit secrets to Git
Restart Node‑RED after change:
node-red-restart


6. Git Integration
6.1 Repository
git@github.com:r14ik/IITK_SMART_PLUG_git_iter1.git

6.2 SSH Authentication
Generate key:
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "jetson-nodered"

Add public key to GitHub
Verify:
ssh -T git@github.com


7. Cloning Repo into Node‑RED
7.1 Stop Node‑RED
node-red-stop

7.2 Backup Existing Files
mkdir ~/node-red-backup
cp -r ~/.node-red/* ~/node-red-backup/

7.3 Clone Repo
rm -rf ~/.node-red
git clone git@github.com:r14ik/IITK_SMART_PLUG_git_iter1.git ~/.node-red

Verify:
cd ~/.node-red
git status


8. Git Ignore Rules (CRITICAL)
Create .gitignore inside ~/.node-red:
node_modules/
.context/
lib/
*.log
.config.runtime.json
flows_cred.json

Commit once:
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Add Node-RED gitignore"
git push


9. Runtime Workflow
9.1 On Raspberry Pi (Development)
Edit flows
Export / save flows.json
Commit & push to GitHub
9.2 On Jetson (Deployment)
cd ~/.node-red
git pull
node-red-restart

Always restart Node‑RED after pulling changes.


